Ennius is chiefly noted for his epic poem called Annales,—i11 which he related, in eighteen books, the entire history of Rome from the earliest times down to his own,— for his saturae, and his tragedies. But he also attempted comedy, and so deserves mention here. He was born at Rudiae in Calabria, in 2⁰9 lac. In ‘204 he was brought by the quaestor M. Porcius Cato from Sardinia to Rome, where he seems to have lived in moderate circumstances as toacher of Greek and as stage poet. In 184 nc. he received the right of Roman citizenship, which he lived to enjoy for fifteen years. None of his comedies have come down to us —not even in fragments of any importance.
